{[%evp 0,32,18,33,13,25,18,23,11,-39,-38,-45,-64,5,5,5,5,1,4,4,4,-51,-11,-16,
-8,-11,14,9,14,5,12,19,32,4,2]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5.
O-O {This old gambit line can be still seen on a high level from time to
time. White invites the opponent to grab another pawn, and it is the beginning
of interesting tactical complications.} Nxe4 {The most challenging reply.
Black doesn't fear of pin because ...d7-d5 will be played with a tempo.} 6. Re1
(6. Nc3 $6 {This dubious move was played by a few strong players.} Nxc3 {This is
the easiest way to refute the Gambit.} (6... dxc3 {is possible too, but I
don't see a reason to enter wild complications that emerge after} 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7
8. Qd5+) 7. bxc3 Be7 {The immediate 7...d5 is equally good.} 8. cxd4 d5 9. Bb5
O-O {Black has successfully solved the development issues.} 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11.
Ne5 Qe8 $15 {White didn't have much for a pawn in Beerdsen, T - Pichot, A Chess.
com INT 2022}) (6. Nxd4 $6 {cannot be recommended either:} d5 7. Bb5 Bd7 8. c4
{There are few decent ways to meet this aggressive idea, but I mostly like} Bc5
$1 9. Nb3 Bxf2+ 10. Rxf2 Nxf2 11. Kxf2 Ne7 $17 {Black has a slight material
advantage, and White's king is unsafe.}) 6... d5 7. Bxd5 {Only this resource
might justify White's previous risky play.} ({After} 7. Nc3 $6 dxc3 8. Bxd5 Be6
9. Bxe4 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Bd6 11. bxc3 O-O-O $15 {Black has the better chances due
to superior pawn structure.}) 7... Qxd5 8. Nc3 {The double pin allows White to
quickly regain the piece.} Qh5 {One of few reasonable ways to retreat the
queen.} 9. Nxe4 ({Bad is} 9. Rxe4+ $2 Be6 10. Nxd4 Qxd1+ 11. Nxd1 O-O-O $17)
9... Be6 10. Bg5 {The most tricky move. Its main idea is to prevent the long
castle.} ({The straighforward} 10. Neg5 {is considered harmless for decades in
view of} O-O-O $1 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Rxe6 Bd6 {This position occurred in many
games, but there are no strong players on White's side. Indeed, Black has the
better attacking prospects here!} {For instance,} 13. Bd2 {(The most common)}
Rhf8 14. h3 Qf5 15. Re1 Rd7 $36 {White's king got under strong pressure in
Popek, J - Ziolkowski, P Sielpa 2004}) ({It is worth mentioning, that the timid} 
10. Nxd4 $6 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 O-O-O {fails to equalize for White because after} 12.
Be3 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Bf5 $15 {Black's powerful bishops seem to be an important
factor in the long term.}) 10... Bd6 {This is the safest approach, although
letting White capture on d6 looks like a definite concession.} ({Black avoids
a little trap:} 10... h6 $6 11. Bf6 $1 {, and then the strong Bf6 makes it
tough for Black to complete his development. For instance,} Qg6 (11... Qd5 12.
c3 dxc3 13. Qe2 $1) 12. Nh4 Qh7 13. Qd3 {Tsyhanchuk,S - Tanenbaum,Z Chess.com
INT 2022}) (10... Bb4 {is playable but after} 11. c3 dxc3 12. bxc3 Ba5 13. h4
$1 {the poor Qh5 offers White an interesting compensation for a pawn.}) 11.
Nxd6+ ({In comparison to 10...h6, now this move isn't effective at all} 11. Bf6
$6 Bxh2+ $1 {This is the point! Black wins material.} 12. Nxh2 Qxd1 13. Raxd1
gxf6 14. Nxf6+ Kf8 15. Nf3 Rd8 $15 {Capaliku,A - Tomazini,Z Nova Gorica 2015})
({the original} 11. c4 {shouldn't confuse at all:} O-O 12. c5 Be5 {The only,
but decent square!} 13. Nxe5 Qxd1 14. Raxd1 Nxe5 15. Rxd4 Nc6 16. Rd3 Rfe8 {
Black had a comfortable endgame in Friedel, J - Onischuk, A San Diego 2004}) (11.
h4 {also doesn't change much:} h6 12. Nxd6+ ({Worse is} 12. Bf6 $6 O-O 13. Nxd6
cxd6 14. Bxd4 Bg4 $17 {White's king was very exposed in Annaberdiyev, B -
Shahade, G Lichess.org INT 2021}) 12... cxd6 13. Bf4 Qd5 14. c3 O-O-O {Black
had no problems in Thompson, B - Kitson, K ICCF email 2019}) 11... cxd6 12. Bf4 {
Both d-pawns are attacked now.} Qc5 {Fro some reason, this natural move is
only Black's 3rd choice by statistics.} 13. Ng5 (13. c3 O-O 14. cxd4 Qd5 $11 {
Perez Bolanos,J - Cuadrado Carmona,J Salobrena 2020}) 13... O-O 14. Ne4 Qf5 15.
Qd2 ({After} 15. Bxd6 Rfe8 16. Ng3 Qd5 17. Ba3 a5 {White got under pressure
because of misplaced Ba3. Timmermans,M - Shyam,S Dieren 2009}) 15... Qg6 16.
Nxd6 Bd5 {Black has some advantage due to his strong Bd5. Tanase, M - Ryabov, A
ICCF email 2016} *

