{[%evp 0,42,18,13,25,26,23,11,11,5,-33,-59,-59,-14,-19,-11,-11,-21,11,-19,-23,
-23,-11,-10,-15,-26,-13,-11,-35,0,-9,-15,34,34,37,1,1,1,54,27,1,-7,47,9,-1]} 1.
e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. e5 {The most common choice. White is
relying on the strong Pe5, that heavily restricts the mobility of the
opponent's pieces.} d5 {There are a few possible alternatives, but I see no
reason for deviating from this most natural move.} 6. Bb5 {White has to waste
a tempo for retreating the bishop. On the other hand, pinning the Nc6 is a
vital measure anyways.} Ne4 7. Nxd4 {There is nothing better than capturing
the pawn.} (7. O-O Bc5 8. Nxd4 O-O {is a transposition.}) 7... Bc5 {it turns
out, that Black can ignore the threat of Nxc6.} (7... Bd7 {is more common, but
I like the active text move.}) 8. Be3 $1 {This is the most challenging move.} (
{In case of} 8. Nxc6 Bxf2+ 9. Kf1 bxc6 10. Bxc6+ Kf8 {White isn't in time to
capture the rook because of 11...Ba6+. The best is} 11. Qd3 ({But not} 11. c4
$2 Qh4 12. Bxd5 Bg4 13. Qd3 Bb6 14. Be3 Ng3+ $19) 11... Bf5 12. Qf3 Bd7 $1 {
This important tactical resource allows Black to maintain the initiative.} 13.
e6 Bxe6 14. Bxa8 Qxa8 15. Nc3 Bb6 {Black has more than sufficient compensation
for an exchange. Coelho,R - Vivas Zamora,F Chess.com INT 2021}) ({Another
common continuation is} 8. O-O O-O 9. Bxc6 ({The ''greedy''} 9. Nxc6 $6 bxc6
10. Bxc6 {is refuted by} Ba6 $1 11. Bxa8 (11. Qxd5 {is what White played in
most of the games but after} Bxf1 12. Qxe4 Bb5 $1 13. Nc3 Bxc6 14. Qxc6 Bd4 {
Black has nearly the decisive domination due to strong Bd4.}) 11... Bxf1 12.
Kxf1 Qh4 $36 {with a powerful initiative. White's lack of development starts
to tell.}) 9... bxc6 10. Be3 {An important consolidating move. It is too
dangerous to ignore Black's pressure along the a7-g1 diagonal.} ({Too risky is
} 10. Nxc6 Qd7 11. Nd4 {White wastes 2 tempi to grab the pawn, and now Black
can claim the power of his bishops with} Qe7 12. Bf4 f6 $1 {A well-timed break.
} 13. e6 Bxe6 14. c3 Bf7 {Black has at least solved all his problems. Rogers,
I - Pavlovic,M Sokobanja 1989}) ({Worse is} 10. f3 $2 f6 $1 11. fxe4 fxe5 12.
Rxf8+ Qxf8 13. c3 dxe4 $17 {Black was just up a pawn in Tasci, O - Rzayev, B
Konya 2019}) 10... Qe8 $1 {A clever idea. Besides covering the Pc6 Black also
takes control of e-file.} 11. Nd2 {White is interested in neutralizing the
strong centralized knight of the opponent.} ({The main idea of the last move
is well illustrated in the following case:} 11. f3 $2 Nf6 $1 {The Be3 is
vulnerable!} 12. f4 Ng4 13. Qd2 f6 {White was on the verge of collapse in
Lozynskyi,B - Vakulenko,A Chortkiv 2020}) 11... Bb6 {I like this rare
prophylactic move. Black can do with an exchange on e4 because it will weaken
the Pe5 either.} 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qh5 {The only way to defend the pawn, but
it meets a concrete reaction.} (13. a4 $6 {, as in Golizadeh,A - Vivas Zamora,
F Chess.com INT 2021 runs into} Ba6 $1 $146 14. Re1 Rd8 {The pin along the
d-file causes White lots of problems.}) 13... f5 $1 {Black takes the
opportunity of trading queens in favourable redaction.} 14. Qxe8 Rxe8 $11 {
Black had no problems in Schut, L - Ohanyan, E Chess.com INT 2021}) 8... O-O 9.
Nxc6 {Finally White grabs the pawn. It is the only way to fight for an
advantage.} (9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. O-O Qe8 {transposes to 8.0-0}) 9... bxc6 10. Bxc5
(10. Bxc6) 10... Nxc5 11. Bxc6 Rb8 12. Qxd5 ({After} 12. O-O Ba6 13. Re1 Rxb2 {
the active Rb2 provides Black with a sufficient counter-play in all the cases:}
14. Qxd5 ({Or} 14. Qd4 Rxc2 15. Na3 Nb3 16. axb3 Rxc6 $11 {Bibko,I - Frolov,D
Novosibirsk 2002}) 14... Rxc2 15. Na3 Rc3 16. Qxd8 Rxd8 {Black had a
comfortable endgame in Shaposhnikov, E - Varavin, V St Petersburg 2000}) 12...
Qe7 $1 {It is better for Black to not leave the queens on the board for a
while.} 13. O-O Rxb2 14. Nc3 {The most popular choice. White gives his
material advantage to centralize the pieces.} ({The attempt to retain the pawn
with} 14. Na3 {isn't so effective in view of} Be6 15. Qd4 Rb6 16. Bf3 ({
Harmless is} 16. Bb5 Nd7 17. Rfd1 Nxe5 18. Qxe5 Qxa3 $11) 16... Nd7 17. Qc3 Qb4
$132 {Black had an excellent play for a pawn in Totsky, L-Varavin, V
Khabarovsk 1990}) 14... Rxc2 15. Qd4 {[#] Vacating d5 for the knight. Black
has to be careful.} Ne6 16. Qd3 Rb2 17. Nd5 ({After} 17. Qe3 {Engelberg, J -
De Meye, J ICCF email 2014 the simplest way to equalize is} Qc5 $146 18. Qxc5
Nxc5 {The isolated Pc7 is compensated by active Rb2. For instance,} 19. Nd5 Be6
20. f4 Rd8 21. Rfd1 Kf8 $11) 17... Qc5 18. Rac1 Qd4 {Back reasonably insists
on the trade.} 19. Qa3 {This is what we will play i.p} (19. Qf5 {This was Lu,M
- Milikow,Y Belgrade 2022} {Here I suggest the prophylactic} Kh8 $146 20. Rcd1
Rd2 21. Rxd2 ({White achieves nothing special also with} 21. Nf6 Ng5 $1 22.
Rxd2 Qxd2 $11) 21... Qxd2 $11 {Black's king is relatively safe, so the
position is balanced.}) 19... Rd2 20. Qa5 {, as in Pap,M - Todorovic,G Paracin
2022 can be naturally met with} Rd8 $146 21. Ne7+ Kf8 22. Nxc8 Rxc8 $11 {
Black has excellent piece coordination, so all the problems are solved.} *

