{[%evp 0,34,25,26,23,11,11,11,3,-48,-23,-23,-13,-52,-32,13,0,-65,-65,-65,-72,
-53,-59,-54,-24,-17,-15,-15,-7,0,-11,-15,-3,-15,-8,-24,-34]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ ({The original} 6. d3 $6 {was
successfully employed by the great David Bronstein. However, objectively it puts
White in danger.} h6 7. Nf3 e4 8. Nd4 ({After} 8. Qe2 Nxc4 9. dxc4 Bc5 {
Black's pawns majority is supported by the bishop pair. It provides Black more
than sufficient compensation for a pawn:} 10. Nfd2 O-O 11. Nb3 (11. O-O Bg4
12. Qe1 Re8 13. Nb3 Bd6 $40 {leaves White's king with no protection.}) 11...
Bg4 12. Qf1 Bb4+ 13. c3 Be7 $36 {White struggles to complete development. Zeng,
C - Vidit,S Xingtai 2019}) ({The brave} 8. dxe4 Nxc4 9. Qd4 {is what great
David chose a long time ago. Alas, such ''romantic'' piece sacrifices are easily
refuted in our era:} Nd6 $1 {The most convincing!} 10. Nc3 (10. e5 Nf5 11. Qa4+
Qd7 $19 {also leaves nowhere.}) 10... Nfxe4 $1 {A little tactic that enables
Black to immediately destroy the pawns centre.} 11. Nxe4 Qe7 12. O-O Nxe4 13.
Re1 f5 {Black should be able to convert the extra piece.}) 8... Bc5 {Black
gains another tempo by attacking the opponent's knight.} 9. c3 {A sad
necessity.} O-O $146 {This natural move is a novelty.} (9... Bxd4 10. cxd4 O-O
{was also fine in Hicks, E-Barnes, R Nelson 1912}) 10. O-O exd3 11. Bxd3 Qxd5 {
Black's pieces are more active, so White should be careful.}) 6... c6 7. dxc6
bxc6 8. Bf1 {Among the possible retreats this one looks most artificial. It
can be only justified in case Black captures on h3, but the loss of tempo
should tell.} ({The other natural retreat} 8. Ba4 $2 {might lead to a quick
disaster:} h6 9. Nf3 e4 10. Ne5 ({Or} 10. Qe2 Be6 11. Ne5 Qd4 12. Bxc6+ Nxc6
13. Nxc6 Qc5 $19) 10... Qd4 $1 {This is the point! White loses material in
view of poor Ba4} 11. Bxc6+ Nxc6 12. Nxc6 Qc5 13. Nxa7 Rxa7 $19 {Although
White currently has 3 pawns for a piece, Balck is absolutely winning. None of
White's pieces are developed, and the king is under fire.}) 8... h6 9. Nh3 Bc5 {
Of course, there is no need for Black to part with his bishop and let White host
the bishop on the long diagonal.} 10. d3 O-O 11. Nc3 Re8 12. Be2 $146 {This
modest move is the lesser evil for White.} ({After} 12. Be3 $6 Bxe3 13. fxe3
Qb6 14. Qd2 Qxb2 {White was on the verge of collapse in Savchenko,B -
Terletsky,O Chess.com INT 2021}) 12... Nb7 $1 {Black has time for
centralization. The Na5 was definitely misplaced.} 13. O-O Nd6 {White's main
issue is the poor Nh3. The extra pawn doesn't really tell.} 14. Bf3 Qc7 15. Na4
({After} 15. Kh1 Bf5 16. Ng1 Rad8 $36 {White's pieces are too passive, and ...
e5-e4 is to follow soon.}) 15... Bd4 16. c3 Bb6 17. Nxb6 axb6 $36 {Despite
exchanging Black's strong bishop White's position remains uncomfortable
because of poor Nh3 and weak Pd3.} *

