{[%evp 0,52,25,15,11,11,15,8,10,-17,0,0,-2,0,0,0,11,-7,115,115,165,82,48,66,64,
23,95,114,114,126,170,130,143,141,182,148,269,0,84,58,67,39,77,38,58,58,63,63,
75,88,80,19,75,36,36]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6.
Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 {The starting point. This position is known for a few
centuries, and it can be still seen on the highest level.} 8. Qf3 {Quite an
ambitious, but a risky continuation. White refuses to waste a tempo for
retreating the bishop, but the Qf3 is placed awkwardly.} cxb5 $5 {This is only
Black's 8th choice by statistics! Black sacrifices the exchange, but White's
queen is gonna be in the danger zone. It is the beginning of interesting tactical
complications.} ({Instead, the main continuations} 8... Be7) ({and} 8... Rb8 {
also score well on practice.}) 9. Qxa8 Qc7 $1 {Not only activating the queen,
but also threatening ...Nc6, leaving the Qa8 locked.} 10. Qf3 {White can't
wait with retreating the queen.} ({The careless} 10. Nc3 $2 Nc6 11. Nxb5 Qd7 {
put White in big danger in view of poor Qa8 in Profili, E - Travadon, L Europe
Echecs INT 2020.} {The lesser evil was} 12. O-O $146 Be7 13. Nxa7 Nxa7 14. d3
O-O $17 {, but even then Black has a powerful initiative - the minor pieces
overwhelm the rook, while White's passers have no much value yet.}) 10... Nc6
{There is no way White can prevent the nasty ...Nc6-d4.} 11. c3 Bg4 {Gaining
an important tempo by attacking the Qf3. This line well illustrates the
drawback of 8.Qf3.} 12. Qg3 ({The other moves are clearly worse:} 12. Qd3 $2
Nb4 13. Qxb5+ Bd7 {leads to major material losses.}) ({Or} 12. Qe3 $2 h6 13.
Nf3 Nd5 14. Qe4 Nf4 {The activity of Black's pieces is threatening.} 15. O-O f5
16. Qe3 e4 17. Nd4 Nxd4 18. cxd4 Bd6 $19 {Black dominates over the board.})
12... Nd4 $1 {An important tactical resource that is based on the vulnerability
of Bc1.} 13. Na3 {Again, the only response.} Ne2 {An illustrative position!
The strong Ne2 interrupts White's piece coordination, and the Ke1 is stuck in
the centre.} 14. Qd3 ({The materialistic approach cannot be recommended here:} 
14. Nxb5 Qb8 15. Qd3 {runs into} h6 $1 {The poor piece coordination leaves
White nothing better than} 16. f3 Nxc1 17. Qc4 (17. Rxc1 $6 Bd7 $17 {leads to
an inferior redaction: White still loses the piece.}) 17... Nd3+ $1 {An
elegant way to parry the threat on f7.} 18. Qxd3 Bd7 $36 {Both White's knights
are hanging, so Black manages to practically even material. Of course, the
initiative is on Black's side in view of more active pieces.}) ({Too risky is
also} 14. Qe3 $6 Bxa3 15. bxa3 Nd5 16. Qe4 Ndf4 17. f3 Bd7 $36 {The lack of
development in White's camp starts to tell.}) 14... Nf4 {The knight did its
job!} 15. Qxb5+ Bd7 16. Qc4 {For a moment, it looks like Black's initiative
comes to an end and he has to accept the queen's trade, but...} Qb7 $1 {
It turns out, that Black can do with losing the Pf7!} 17. f3 {it is better for
White to deviate from capturing it.} ({In case of} 17. Qxf7+ Kd8 18. f3 Bxa3
19. bxa3 $2 ({The lesser evil is} 19. Qc4 {, but after} Be7 {Black's
superiority is undeniable.}) {Black wins on a spot with} 19... Qa6 $1 20. c4
Be8 21. Qxg7 Rg8 $19) 17... Bxa3 18. O-O ({After} 18. bxa3 O-O {White has to
castle anyways.}) 18... O-O 19. bxa3 Bb5 {Although White manages to move his
king from the centre. it is still rather unsafe.} 20. Qb3 Qa6 21. d3 {It is
necessary to unblock the Bc1.} Nxd3 22. Qc2 $146 {White is trying to maintain
his material advantage.} ({After} 22. Nh3 Nc5 23. Qb4 Bxf1 24. Qxc5 Bc4 {
Black was fine in Chandra, A - Theodorou, N Saint Louis 2019}) 22... h6 23. Nh3
e4 {I mostly like this energetic move. Black makes use of his more active
pieces.} 24. fxe4 Nxe4 25. Be3 Ba4 $1 {An important resource. There is just
one possible square for a retreat.} 26. Qe2 Nxc3 {the strong knights offer
Black a sufficient compensation for an exchange.} *

