{[%evp 0,36,25,11,11,15,15,11,11,-17,-2,-2,11,-7,-7,-7,-7,-70,-45,-3,-2,10,-3,
-3,33,52,43,43,43,43,3,18,13,5,5,6,37,40,18]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4.
Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Be2 {By far the most common move.
White retreats his bishop without blocking the d-pawn, as after 8.Bd3. On the
other hand, it diminishes White's control of e4, so Black's next move is
obvious.} h6 {A well-timed move. Since e4 isn't vacant for the knight, White
has to either play the awkward 9.Nh3 or provoke the nasty ...e5-e4.} 9. Nf3 {
The top choice, although in recent years 9.Nh3} e4 10. Ne5 (10. Ng1 $2 {
isn't a considerable option:} Bc5 11. d3 Qb6 {is already crushing.}) 10... Bc5
{The most aggressive choice. Black prevents the consolidating d2-d4 and makes
a threat of ...Qd4.} (10... Bd6 {is the most common alternative, and then after
} 11. d4 exd3 12. Nxd3 O-O {Black retains a decent compensation for a pawn.})
11. c3 {The most common continuation. White prevents the nasty ...Qd4 and
makes ..d2-d4 possible.} ({Clearly bad is} 11. f4 $2 O-O 12. c3 Nd5 13. d4 exd3
14. Qxd3 f6 {White's position was already lost in view of exposed Ke1 in
Pokazanjev,N -Yemelin,V Sochi 2007}) ({The main alternative is} 11. O-O {
, and then Black has few good-looking possibilities, but I mostly like} Qd6 $5
{The tactical ideas with ...Ng4 allow Black to immediately regain the pawn.}
12. d4 ({Bad is} 12. Ng4 $2 Bxg4 13. Bxg4 h5 14. Bh3 Ng4 15. g3 {A sad
necessity.} Nxf2 16. Rxf2 h4 {Black had the decisive attack in Koronowski, H -
Klimakovs,S ICCF email 2008}) 12... Qxd4 13. Qxd4 Bxd4 14. Nc4 {The only move.
The only disadvantage of Black's position is the isolated Pc6, but it's not a
big deal.} Nxc4 15. Bxc4 O-O 16. Nc3 Re8 {Black takes care of Pe4 and
mobilizes the forces.} 17. Rd1 Bxc3 (17... Be5 $5 {also seems to offer Black a
comfortable play.}) 18. bxc3 Be6 {White's bishop pair is compensated by
Black's superior pawn structure. Vohl,G - Mauro,L ICCF email 2017}) 11... Qc7
12. d4 ({Too risky is} 12. f4 exf3 13. Nxf3 Ng4 $1 {Black immediately starts
to put pressure on White's exposed king.} 14. b4 ({After} 14. d4 Bd6 15. b4 Nb7
16. Na3 Nxh2 {Black had a free attack in Laine, E - Vetter, G ICCF email 2011})
14... Bd6 ({Instead,} 14... Nf2 15. Qc2 Nxh1 16. bxc5 {leads to an unbalanced
position with mutual chances.}) 15. bxa5 Bxh2 16. Kf1 Bg3 {Black's initiative
compensates for a piece, to say the least. Trautz,R-Rulfs,E DESC email 2016})
12... exd3 13. Nxd3 Bd6 {The c3 square is blocked, so it makes it tougher for
White to complete his development.} 14. Nd2 {It is better for White to
immediately take care of development.} ({After} 14. h3 O-O 15. O-O Bf5 16. b4
Nc4 $36 {White's extra pawn didn't have value when most of the pieces are still
undeveloped. Sarenac,I - Todorovic,G Zlatibor 2008}) (14. g3 {doesn't look
attractive either:} O-O 15. O-O Bh3 {Black exploits the weakness of light
squares around White's king.} 16. Re1 Rad8 17. Bf1 Bxf1 18. Rxf1 Rfe8 {The
activity of all Black's pieces overwhelms the pawn. Fernandez Ballon, A -
Leisebein,P Remote email 2012}) 14... O-O 15. b4 ({The passive} 15. Nf3 Bf5 16.
O-O {allows Black to perfectly spot all the pieces:} Rad8 17. b4 Nd5 18. Bd2
Nc4 $44 {Ponting,A - Hladky,O FICGS email 2008}) 15... Nb7 16. Nc4 {White is
trying to release the pressure on his k-side by exchanging the Bd6.} Nd5 17.
Bb2 ({After} 17. Nxd6 Nxc3 18. Qc2 Nxe2 19. Qxe2 Qxd6 {Black has nothing to
worry about.}) 17... Bf5 18. g3 Bh3 {The Ke1 is stuck in the centre, and Black
seems to have an excellent play for a pawn. Goncharov,I - Klimakovs,S ICCF
email 2010} *

