{[%evp 0,36,25,11,15,15,11,11,17,11,-7,-7,-7,-7,1,0,0,-3,10,-63,-15,-20,1,5,5,
-12,16,20,12,4,0,-46,-55,-14,-12,11,20,-47,-13]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6
4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Be2 h6 9. Nh3 {This original
retreat has practically replaced the more natural 9.Nf3. Now Black doesn't
manage to gain lots of space with ...e5-e4, but it costs White placing the
knight awkwardly.} Bd6 10. d3 {The most flexible continuation. White unblocks
the Bc1 and vacates d2 for his queen's knight.} (10. Nc3 {mostly doesn't have
an independent value} O-O 11. O-O {A risky approach. The Nh3 is stuck for a
while, although White is intending to play ..Kh1, Ng1, e.t.c.} (11. d3 c5 {
transposes to text.}) 11... c5 12. Bf3 Rb8 13. d3 {This was Riehle,M - Kovalev,
V Chess.com INT 2020} {At this point Black could have developed a powerful
initiative with} Rb6 $1 $146 14. Kh1 Nc6 15. Ng1 Nd4 $36 {The strong Nd4
dominates over White's pieces, and the Rb6 is ready to join the attack via 6th
rank.}) (10. d4 $6 {is premature, although it was played by a few strong players}
Qc7 $1 {It makes sense for Black to keep the queens on the board.} ({Less
energetic is} 10... O-O 11. dxe5 Bxe5 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Nf4 Bf5 14. Nd3 {
White managed to stabilize the situation and eventually the extra pawn got
converted. Short, N - Golod, V ICC INT 2000}) 11. dxe5 Bxe5 {Now, when the
central files are open White starts to suffer from a lack of development.} 12. f4
Bd6 13. O-O {This position was reached in Steinitz, W-Blackburne, J Vienna 1898}
O-O $1 $146 14. Nc3 Re8 15. Kh1 Bb7 $36 {, followed by ...Rad8 would have
offered Black more than full compensation for a pawn. White struggles to
complete his development, and the Kh1 is in permanent danger.}) 10... c5 {
Mostly this move is played after 10...0-0, but I see no reason for delaying it:
Black takes more control of d4 and makes c6 vacant for the knight.} 11. Nc3 ({
I also examined} 11. Ng1 $146 O-O 12. Nf3 {The knight s getting back, but it
took a few tempi.} Bb7 13. O-O Qb6 {A vital move. The rooks are connected now,
and the Qb6 is actively placed.} 14. Na3 Rad8 15. Nd2 Bb8 $44 {White's pieces
are somewhat cramped, and Black has excellent attacking prospects.}) (11. Nd2
O-O 12. O-O Rb8 {Now the Bc1 is tied with defending the pawn. Also, the Rb8
might sometimes join the attack along the 6th rank.} 13. Ne4 {White is
naturally aiming to simplify the matters and stabilize the situation.} (13. Bf3
Bc7 14. Re1 {, as in Akrill, R - Stefanov, P ICCF email 2020} {can be well met by}
Rb6 $1 {A decent move that is mainly aimed at transferring the knight to d4.}
15. Kh1 g5 $1 {White's next move is forced in view of ...g5-g4.} 16. Ne4 Nxe4
17. dxe4 Rd6 $36 {Black is firmly in a control due to control over the d-file
and poor Nh3.}) ({Too passive is} 13. b3 Nc6 14. Kh1 Nd4 15. Bf3 Bc7 {Black
reached the most harmonious setup.} 16. Ng1 Nd5 $36 {White was very cramped in
Jimenez Melguizo,F - Rodriguez,L ICCF email 2019}) 13... Nd5 $5 $146 ({A bit
slower is} 13... Nc6 14. Kh1 Nd5 15. Ng1 Be7 {The chances were mutual in Pupo
Perez,H - Kahl,F LSS email 2018}) 14. Kh1 ({After} 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. Bg4 f5 16.
Bf3 f4 {most of White's pieces are placed awfully.}) 14... Bxh3 15. gxh3 f5 {
The most active White's piece is chased from the centre.} 16. Nc3 Ne7 17. Rg1
Kh7 {Black has excellent compensation for a pawn in view of superior pawn
structure and more active pieces.}) 11... O-O 12. Ng1 {This position was
reached in Aronian, L - Kamsky, G Chess.com INT 2022} ({In case of} 12. Bf3 Rb8
13. Ng1 {Black can extend the initiative with} c4 14. Nge2 {This was Vykouk,J
- Lobanov,S Chess.com INT 2020} {Now the simple} cxd3 $146 15. Qxd3 Rb6 16. O-O
Ba6 $36 {would have put White in big danger.}) {Here my new natural idea is}
12... Qb6 $146 {Black waits until White will play Ng1-f3 to place the bishop
on b7.} 13. Nf3 ({After} 13. Bf3 Nc6 14. Nge2 Be6 15. O-O Rad8 {the opposition
along the d-file causes White lots of problems.} 16. b3 Nd4 17. Nxd4 cxd4 18. Ne4
(18. Na4 Qc7 $15) 18... Nxe4 19. dxe4 Qc6 $44 {The pressure along the c-file
provides Black with an undeniable compensation.}) 13... Bb7 14. O-O ({After} 14. Nd2
Rad8 15. O-O Bb8 {White has to both with ...c5-c4 or e5-e4. In both cases, the
lack of development should tell.} 16. Bf3 (16. b3 $6 e4 $1 {is more
problematic for White.}) 16... c4 $44 {Black has a promising compensation for
a pawn.}) 14... Rad8 15. Be3 {White is getting closer to connecting the rooks,
although his minor pieces are not placed well.} e4 {By opening the d-file
Black increases the pressure.} 16. Nd2 exd3 17. cxd3 Rfe8 $1 {It is time for
involving the other rook.} ({Hardly Black has to worry about regaining
material too much:} 17... Qxb2 18. Qc1 Qxc1 19. Rfxc1 {, and the endgame is
slightly better for White in view of weak Pc5.}) 18. Bf3 ({The ''greedy''} 18.
Rb1 $2 {is refuted by} Qc7 $1 19. h3 {White has no other reasonable way of
covering the pawn.} Rxe3 $1 20. fxe3 Bh2+ 21. Kh1 Bxg2+ 22. Kxg2 Qg3+ 23. Kh1
Qxh3 {with a decisive attack.}) 18... Qxb2 {Black regains the pawn in
a favourable situation. All the problems are solved.} *

