{[%evp 0,36,25,15,15,17,19,19,20,-7,-7,-7,0,8,10,10,10,-32,-2,-52,0,0,7,0,0,
-10,-2,-2,-42,-46,-3,-45,-50,-54,-61,-106,-60,-60,-83]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.
Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Bd3 Nd5 {An important
move. White's last move was aimed at securing e4 for the knight, so Black
reasonably makes ....f7-f5 possible. Also, f4 is now vacant for his knight.} 9.
h4 {The main alternative to 9.Nf3. By advancing the h-pawn White takes a
definite risk, since the potential residence of White's monarch on the k-side
is gonna be unsafe. On the other hand, the active Ng5 puts Black's k-side
under some pressure.} ({The greedy} 9. Nxh7 $2 {is easily refuted by} Nf4 $1
10. Nxf8 {Koenig,M - Obrien,G LSS email 2018} Nxg2+ $1 $146 11. Kf1 Bh3 {
with a decisive attack.}) ({Dubious is also} 9. Ne4 $6 Nf4 10. Bf1 f5 {
This is the point! White's pieces are pushed back.} 11. Nec3 ({After} 11. Ng3
Bc5 12. c3 Bb6 13. d4 Qe7 $36 {White suffered from the lack of development in
Askarov,B - Wen,Y Albena 2015}) 11... Bc5 {The activity of Black's minor
pieces is getting more and more dangerous.} 12. d3 ({After} 12. Na4 Bxf2+ 13.
Kxf2 Qd4+ {Black regains the pawn and maintains his merits.}) 12... O-O {
Black doesn't fear exchange on f4.} 13. g3 ({After} 13. Bxf4 $2 exf4 14. Be2
Qb6 {White suffers heavy material losses.}) 13... Re8 $1 {It turns out, that
Black can leave the active Nf4 for a while. Its capture will significantly
increase Black's attacking potential due to the open e-file.} 14. Qd2 {This
awkward move tells by itself.} Nd5 15. Bg2 e4 $36 {The activity of Black's
pieces overwhelms White's extra pawn. Thompson, B - Brasier, J ICCF email 2017})
9... h6 {This natural move is only Black's 4th choice by statistics, but I
find it the most consistent.} ({The more common continuations are} 9... Nf4) (
9... Qc7) ({and} 9... Be7 {in all the cases Black seems to have decent play
for a pawn, but the text is the most concrete.}) 10. Qh5 {White has to enter
complications.} (10. Nf3 $6 {leads to an inferior version of main line} Bd6 11.
Nc3 O-O 12. O-O f5 $17 {White got under strong attack in Vasquez Schroder, R -
Kovalev,V Lichess.org INT 2021}) 10... Qf6 {Now White is at crossroads.} 11.
Ne4 ({Bad is} 11. Nxf7 $2 Nf4 12. Qxe5+ Kxf7 13. Qxa5 Bd6 14. Kf1 Nxd3 15. cxd3
Bf5 $19 {White's position was ruined, and the Kf1 got under decisive attack.
Meyer,F - Krastev,A Hofheim 2017}) ({In case of} 11. Nh7 Rxh7 $1 12. Bxh7 g6 {
White's big material advantage is temporary, as the Bh7 should be trapped soon.
} 13. Qe2 ({Much worse is} 13. Qf3 $2 Qxf3 14. gxf3 Nf6 $17 {The Bh7 is gone,
and White is left with an awful development and pawn structure. Gunina, V -
Muzychuk,A Kazan 2019}) 13... Nf4 14. Qf3 {White struggles to find a safe spot
for his queen.} Bb7 $1 {The most active way of development.} 15. Nc3 {White
needs to cover his queen from attack along the diagonal.} c5 16. Ne4 Qg7 17. h5
{White is trying to liberate the bishop or at least damage the opponent's pawn
structure.} (17. d4 {is well met by} O-O-O $1 18. Bxf4 exf4 19. O-O-O {This
was Popov, I - Moskalenko, A Moscow 2018} {Black should have played} cxd4 $146
20. Qxf4 Nc6 $1 21. Rhe1 Be7 $15 {The minor pieces seem to overweight the rook.
}) 17... O-O-O 18. hxg6 fxg6 {Black has reached a harmonious setup.} 19. d3
Qxh7 20. Bxf4 {Liquidating the strong Nf4 is White's undeniable achievement,
but it doesn't solve all the issues.} exf4 21. Qxf4 Qg8 22. O-O Nc6 {The
powerful bishops provide Black an excellent play. Simal Moreira,L - Cvak,R ICCF
email 2017}) 11... Qe6 12. b3 {White is naturally aiming to complete the
development of his q-side pieces.} ({In case of} 12. Ng5 Qf6 13. Ne4 {Black
can either accept a draw by repetition or try (especially against lower-rated
opponent!)} Qe7 $5 14. Be2 (14. Nbc3 Nf4 15. Qf3 Qd7 $132) 14... g6 15. Qf3 Be6
{, obtaining a definite compensation for a pawn.}) (12. Ng3 {, as in Cvak, R-
Tylecek, D LSS email 2019 looks rather passive as the Ng3 will be out of play.
Here my new natural idea is} g6 $146 13. Qd1 Bg7 {Black harmoniously places
the pieces, while White struggles to activate them.} 14. Be2 ({After} 14. Nc3
f5 15. Nxd5 cxd5 16. Bb5+ Nc6 {White is very cramped as well.}) 14... O-O 15.
d3 f5 16. O-O c5 $44 {Black has full control over the centre, and White's
pieces are well restricted.}) 12... g6 {A well-timed move. White struggles to
find a safe square for his queen.} 13. Qe2 ({After} 13. Qd1 f5 14. Nec3 Bg7 15.
Nxd5 cxd5 16. Bb5+ Nc6 {Black has superiority in the centre and great
attacking prospects.}) 13... f5 14. Nec3 {We have been following the game
Poetsch,H - Eichler,C Schwarzach 2017} ({Much worse is} 14. Ng3 $2 Bg7 15. Bb2
Nf4 16. Qf1 Nxd3+ 17. cxd3 c5 {White's position is ruined.}) 14... Nf4 $146 15.
Qf1 ({After} 15. Qf3 Bb7 16. Qg3 O-O-O 17. Bf1 Bd6 $36 {White's pieces are too
undeveloped.}) 15... Bb7 16. Bb2 O-O-O {The pressure along the d-file forces
White to part with the extra pawn.} 17. Ba6 Nxg2+ 18. Qxg2 Bxa6 {In this
unbalanced position Black's chances are by no means worse.} *

