{[%evp 0,40,25,15,14,39,14,14,14,14,14,2,21,44,31,28,32,18,22,23,23,20,20,35,
45,29,45,5,6,21,-22,32,-1,-24,64,15,19,-20,-9,-24,-19,-14,-19]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Nc3 {A well-known theoretical position, that can be
reached with different move orders. Now Black is at crossroads.} a6 {As usual,
this prophylactic move is mainly aimed at securing a7 for the bishop. Now
there are many possibilities at White's disposal.} ({I prefer to deviate from
the most popular} 5... d6 {in view of} 6. Na4 Bb6 {I believe, that White's
bishop pair might tell in the long run, although Black's position is very
solid.}) 6. Bg5 {The most common by far, although the pin doesn't seem to
bother Black.} ({The timid} 6. a3 {hardly can be considered as challenging for
Black, and after} d6 {White's extra tempo has no significant value. For
instance,} 7. Be3 (7. Bg5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 {transposes}) ({After} 7. h3 Be6
8. Nd5 Bxd5 9. exd5 Ne7 10. Bg5 Ng6 11. Qe2 h6 $15 {White was suffering from
the weak Pd5. Kokol,P - Diermair,A Graz 2012}) 7... Bxe3 8. fxe3 Be6 9. Bxe6
fxe6 10. O-O O-O 11. Qe1 Qe8 {Funnily, Black continues to copy the moves!} 12.
Qg3 Qh5 $11 {Black didn't have any problems in Movsesian, S - Kovalenko, I
Zagreb 2021}) ({Another quiet continuation is} 6. O-O d6 7. Nd5 ({Harmless is} 
7. Be3 Bxe3 8. fxe3 Na5 {By exchanging the strong bc4 Black neutralizes the
pressure along the f-file.} 9. Bb3 Nxb3 10. axb3 O-O {Just,A - Esipenko,A Bad
Wiessee 2016}) 7... Nxd5 {The easiest way to prevent the nasty ..Bg5.} 8. Bxd5
O-O 9. c3 Qf6 {Black has reached a harmonious setup.} 10. Be3 Bxe3 11. fxe3 Qh6
$11 {The position is balanced. Pilz,E-Neumann,U DESC email 2014}) (6. a4 {
has recently gained popularity at a high level.} d6 7. Be3 ({The quieter} 7.
h3 {is well met by} Be6 8. Nd5 Bxd5 9. exd5 Ne7 {White's position feels
somewhat uncomfortable in view of weak Pd5. Taleb Mohamed,A - Van Hoolandt,P
Tromsoe 2014}) 7... Bxe3 8. fxe3 O-O 9. O-O Be6 {The same approach - the pawn
structure that arises after Bxe6 is traditionally safe for Black.} 10. Nd5 ({
In case of} 10. b3 d5 11. exd5 Nxd5 {Black doesn't seem to face problems as
well.}) 10... Bxd5 11. exd5 Ne7 12. e4 a5 13. c3 Ng6 {The Bc4 wasn't effective,
so Black's position feels comfortable. Abdusattorov,N - Aronian,L Chess.com
INT 2022}) (6. Nd5 {was also tried by top players.} Nxd5 {For some reason, 6...
h6 is much more common.} 7. Bxd5 ({In case of} 7. exd5 Nd4 8. Nxd4 Bxd4 9. c3
Bc5 10. O-O O-O $11 {, followed by d7-d6 Black reaches a comfortable position.}
) 7... d6 8. Be3 {This was played by Kramnik and Anand. White is trying to
increase the pressure on f7 by provoking the bishop's trade.} ({After} 8. c3
O-O 9. b4 Ba7 10. a4 h6 11. Be3 Ne7 12. Bb3 Ng6 {Black has comfortably
equalized in Karjakin, S - Aronian, L Leuven 2018}) 8... Bxe3 9. fxe3 O-O 10.
O-O Nb8 $1 {The position is closed, so Black can afford to spend a few tempi for
re-locating the knight. It moves towards f6 in order to consolidate Black's
k-side.} ({After} 10... Ne7 11. Bb3 Ng6 12. Qe1 $1 {, followed by Qg3 White
has some attacking chances.}) 11. b4 ({After} 11. Qd2 Nd7 12. h3 c6 13. Bb3 Nc5
{Black also didn't face any problems in Anand, V - Aronian, L Leuven 2018 Enter
New Game}) 11... Nd7 12. Qd2 c6 13. Bb3 a5 {Black initiates some active play
on the q-side.} 14. a3 Nf6 {The Kg8 is absolutely safe, so Black is absolutely
fine. Kramnik,V - Aronian,L Berlin 2018}) 6... h6 7. Bxf6 ({Riskier is} 7. Bh4
g5 8. Bg3 d6 {Black can do with a somewhat committing g7-g5, while the Bg3 is
gonna be out of play.} 9. Nd2 {A reasonable idea - White's knight moves
towards e3.} (9. a3 Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 $15 {Kirpichnikov,V - Zavoronkov,V Riga 2002
}) 9... Be6 10. h4 g4 11. h5 {Vacating h4 for the bishop.} Qd7 12. a3 {This
was Vlassov, N - Litvinov, M Samara 2014} b5 $1 $146 {Now Black could have
forced the exchange in favourable redaction with} 13. Ba2 ({After} 13. Bd5 Bb6
$15 {Black's simple idea is Bxd5, followed by Ne7.}) 13... Bxa2 14. Rxa2 Rg8
15. Nf1 d5 $15 {White suffers from lack of harmony - the Ra2 is poor.}) 7...
Qxf6 8. Nd5 Qd8 {Black has to temporarily move back, but the unopposite
dark-squared bishop should compensate for all.} 9. c3 d6 10. d4 Ba7 11. dxe5 ({
Another approach is} 11. h3 O-O 12. O-O {White secures the Nf3 to keep the
pressure in the centre.} Be6 13. Re1 Re8 {Both sides involve the rest of
the pieces.} 14. a4 ({After} 14. Qd2 b5 15. Bb3 Na5 $1 16. Qc2 exd4 17. cxd4 c5 $15
{Black took over the initiative due to his strong Ba7. Franzoni,G - Campora,D
Bern 1987}) 14... exd4 {This looks like a definite concession, but Black
manages to activate his pieces.} 15. cxd4 Nb4 $1 {A decent move. The exchange
of knights is helpful for Black.} 16. Qb3 Nxd5 17. Bxd5 Rb8 18. Rac1 Qd7 $11 {
White's superiority in the centre was fully compensated by pressure on pawns
in Yilmaz, M - Pashikian, A Budva 2009}) 11... Nxe5 {it definitely makes sense
for Black to unblock the c-pawn.} 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Qh5 {White attacks the Pe5,
but Black can ignore the threat.} O-O $1 {The simplest.} 14. Qxe5 Re8 15. Qf4
Qd6 $1 {A strong move. The vulnerability of Pe4 provides Black a sufficient
counter-play.} 16. Qf3 {The most challenging move for Black - White is
interested in keeping the extra pawn.} ({After} 16. O-O-O Qxf4+ 17. Nxf4 Bxf2
18. Rhf1 Be3+ 19. Kc2 Bg4 {the bishop pair offers Black comfortable equality.
}) ({Harmless is also} 16. Qxd6 Rxe4+ 17. Ne3 cxd6 18. Bd5 Re7 19. O-O-O Be6
$11) 16... c6 17. Ne3 (17. Nb6 {is well met by} Qg6 $1 18. Nxc8 Qxe4+ 19. Qxe4
Rxe4+ 20. Be2 Rxc8 {, and White has to struggle for equality.}) 17... Be6 {
White is still up a pawn, but it's not for too long.} 18. Be2 ({After} 18. Rd1
Qe5 19. Bxe6 Qxe6 {Black will get the pawn back in a good situation.}) 18... Rad8
19. O-O Bxe3 20. Qxe3 Qd2 {The invasion on the second rank put White under
pressure in Borngaesser,R - Zude,A Bad Neuenahr 1987} *

